# Major-mode leader key in Spacemacs

It's either \`,\` or \`SPC m m\` or \`M-m m\`, which is useful from insert mode. All
the commands listed below should be prefixed with this leader sequence.

# Citations with pandoc-citeproc / --bibliography

As @lukes14 mentions, citations can be inserted in Spacemacs using \`i c\`
[@lukes14].

# Footnotes

Footnotes can be inserted with \`i f\`.[^1]

[^1]: It really works!

# Cross-reference all the things with pandoc-crossref

## References

\`pandoc-crossref\` uses the same citation syntax as \`pandoc-citeproc\`, which is
neat, tidy and simple, but it means you have to run the former before the
latter.

The automatic text output by the filter can be customized via [variables in the
YAML header](http://lierdakil.github.io/pandoc-crossref/#customization).

Prefixes can be customized on a case-by-case basis with the following syntax:
[Prefix @fig:A], or completely suppressed with -@fig:A.

For further tricks and neat features of reference syntax, see
[here](http://lierdakil.github.io/pandoc-crossref/#references).

## Figures

As can be seen in @fig:A, regular images work.

![Caption](A.png){#fig:A}

References to subfigures work nicely as well, see @fig:C.

<div id="fig:group">
![subfigure 1 caption](B.png){#fig:B}

![subfigure 2 caption](C.png){#fig:C}

Caption of figure
</div>

There's even syntax for a subfigure grid with custom column widths, check out
[the details](http://lierdakil.github.io/pandoc-crossref/#subfigure-grid).

## Equations

The equation @eq:A shows that you can reference equations as well.

$$ 1 + 1 = 2 $$ {#eq:A}

## Tables

Tables also work, see @tbl:A.

| a | b | c |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | 2 | 3 |
| 4 | 5 | 6 |

: Table caption {#tbl:A}

## Sections {#sec:sections}

Sections too, see @sec:sections. Don't forget to invoke \`pandoc\` with
\`--number-sections\`. Section numbering can be
[customized](http://lierdakil.github.io/pandoc-crossref/#section-numbering).

## Listings

And even code listings, with the \`codeBlockCaptions\` metadata option.

\`\`\`python
for i in range(10):
    print(i)
\`\`\`

: Listing caption {#lst:A}

